    <item>
      <title>Wine-Staging 10.2 Release Brings Patch For 11 Year Old Bug</title>
      <author>Michael Larabel</author>
      <link>https://www.phoronix.com/news/Wine-Staging-10.2-Released</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.phoronix.com/news/Wine-Staging-10.2-Released</guid>
      <pubDate>Sat, 12 Jul 2025 13:55:26 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>&lt;div class="content"&gt; &lt;div style="float: left; padding: 0 10px 10px;"&gt;&lt;img alt="WINE" src="https://www.phoronix.com/assets/categories/wine.webp" width="100" height="100" /&gt;&lt;/div&gt; It's been a while since there have been any new patches in the Wine-Staging experimental area to note. More patches though have continued working their way from Wine-Staging to upstream/mainline Wine while this weekend Wine-Staging 10.2 is out at 292 patches atop upstream Wine and containing two new patches. &lt;br /&gt; &lt;br /&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.phoronix.com/news/Wine-10.12-Released"&gt;Wine 10.2 released yesterday&lt;/a&gt; with an experimental EGL back-end for the X11 driver, support for Bluetooth Low Energy services, and other enhancements. Wine-Staging 10.2 was then sent out today for this set of 292 extra patches. &lt;br /&gt; &lt;br /&gt;One of the new patches to Wine-Staging is for helping the bug report &lt;a href="https://bugs.winehq.org/show_bug.cgi?id=52278"&gt;Multiple InstallAware based MSI installers fail with 'Runtime error in install: Cannot open AVI' error (Crysis Wars Trial and Patch 1.5, CodeGear RAD Studio 2007/2009)&lt;/a&gt;. That bug report was open since 2021 due to MSI installer failures over AVI errors at run-time. Merged now in mid-2025 with Wine-Staging 10.2 is a patch to animate support AVI msvc codex within COMCTL32 to hopefully address the issue. &lt;br /&gt;&lt;p align="center"&gt;&lt;img src="https://www.phoronix.net/image.php?id=2025&amp;image=wine_2014_bug" alt="Wine bug report" /&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;br /&gt;The other new patch is for bug report &lt;a href="https://bugs.winehq.org/show_bug.cgi?id=36686"&gt;CodeGear RAD Studio 2009 fails on startup (ISAXXMLReader::putFeature method needs to support 'normalize line breaks' feature)&lt;/a&gt;. Yes, for RAD Studio 2009, but the bug report itself was made all the way back in 2014. For dealing with that MSXML has now added support for the  ISAXXMLReader::putFeature normalize-line-breaks option. &lt;br /&gt; &lt;br /&gt;Aside from those new patches, an MSXML3 element properties patch was also updated. The rest of the nearly 300 patches are the same as in prior releases. &lt;br /&gt; &lt;br /&gt;Wine 10.2 and Wine-Staging 10.2 can be downloaded from &lt;a href="https://www.winehq.org/"&gt;WineHQ.org&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/div&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Linux 6.17 Readies EDAC Support For Intel Granite Rapids D, Wildcat Lake, Raptor Lake HX</title>
      <author>Michael Larabel</author>
      <link>https://www.phoronix.com/news/Linux-6.17-EDAC-GNR-D-WCL</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.phoronix.com/news/Linux-6.17-EDAC-GNR-D-WCL</guid>
      <pubDate>Sat, 12 Jul 2025 11:13:03 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>&lt;div class="content"&gt; &lt;div style="float: left; padding: 0 10px 10px;"&gt;&lt;img alt="INTEL" src="https://www.phoronix.com/assets/categories/intel.webp" width="100" height="100" /&gt;&lt;/div&gt; In addition to Intel preparing &lt;a href="https://www.phoronix.com/news/Intel-Bartlett-Lake-Linux-EDAC"&gt;Bartlett Lake S EDAC driver support&lt;/a&gt; for Linux 6.17, several other recent and upcoming Intel processors are also set to see Error Detection and Correction (EDAC) driver coverage with this next version of the Linux kernel. &lt;br /&gt; &lt;br /&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.phoronix.com/search/Wildcat+Lake"&gt;Wildcat Lake&lt;/a&gt; has been seeing a lot of Linux patches recently for this low-power processor series rumored to be the successor to Alder Lake N. The latest on the Wildcat Lake enablement side for Linux is &lt;a href="https://git.kernel.org/pub/scm/linux/kernel/git/ras/ras.git/commit/?h=edac-for-next&amp;id=773d8bb5ba7f64ee708caecb8deb0930bc1e1cf7"&gt;Wildcat Lake SoC support in the iGen6 EDAC driver&lt;/a&gt;. The patch reinforces what was presented in other Linux patches that Wildcat Lake is a mobile derivative of Panther Lake. The EDAC patch confirms one memory controller for Wildcat Lake and the same registers as Meteor Lake P from this error detection and correction side. This EDAC support makes use of the hardware's in-band ECC capability. &lt;br /&gt; &lt;br /&gt;Also queued this week was &lt;a href="https://git.kernel.org/pub/scm/linux/kernel/git/ras/ras.git/commit/?h=edac-for-next&amp;id=05a61c6cb631a13465f9d3cc875b65a21d40568a"&gt;Raptor Lake HX support&lt;/a&gt; being added to the ie31200 EDAC driver. The few lines of code there enables the Raptor Lake HX's out-of-band ECC capability. &lt;br /&gt;&lt;p align="center"&gt;&lt;img src="https://www.phoronix.net/image.php?id=intel-arrow-lake-ddr5&amp;image=arrow_lake_ddr5_1_med" alt="Intel and DDR5 memory" /&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;br /&gt;The other new Intel EDAC driver code readied this week for Linux 6.17 is &lt;a href="https://git.kernel.org/pub/scm/linux/kernel/git/ras/ras.git/commit/?h=edac-for-next&amp;id=9ad08c1115646533097c8a799ad046bf5127b04a"&gt;Granite Rapids D support&lt;/a&gt; for the i10nm EDAC driver. Granite Rapids D uses similar memory controller registers to Granite Rapids server CPUs but with a different memory controller MMIO base address. EDAC support now ready for Intel Granite Rapids D with the upcoming Linux 6.17 cycle. &lt;br /&gt; &lt;br /&gt;A lot of new hardware support and feature code is brewing for &lt;a href="https://www.phoronix.com/search/Linux+6.17"&gt;Linux 6.17&lt;/a&gt;. The merge window should be open by early August while the stable kernel will be out by early October.&lt;/div&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>NVIDIA Publishes RTXNTC 0.7 Beta For Neural Texture Compression</title>
      <author>Michael Larabel</author>
      <link>https://www.phoronix.com/news/NVIDIA-RTXNTC-0.7-Beta</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.phoronix.com/news/NVIDIA-RTXNTC-0.7-Beta</guid>
      <pubDate>Sat, 12 Jul 2025 10:55:14 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>&lt;div class="content"&gt; &lt;div style="float: left; padding: 0 10px 10px;"&gt;&lt;img alt="NVIDIA" src="https://www.phoronix.com/assets/categories/nvidia.webp" width="100" height="100" /&gt;&lt;/div&gt; NVIDIA software engineers ended out the week by releasing a new beta of their RTX Neural Texture Compression (NTC) SDK. The RTXNTC software is NVIDIA's interesting solution for compressing material texture sets with very promising results for helping to reduce game data sizes moving forward. &lt;br /&gt; &lt;br /&gt;RTX Neural Texture Compression is interesting from a technical perspective and works with Windows and Linux but works best using NVIDIA GPUs although Intel and AMD graphics can work with RTXNTC too. &lt;br /&gt; &lt;br /&gt;&lt;p align="center"&gt;&lt;img src="https://www.phoronix.net/image.php?id=2025&amp;image=nvidia_ntc_pipeline" alt="NVIDIA RTX NTC pipeline graphic" /&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;br /&gt;Friday's release of the RTXNTC 0.7 Beta for Windows brings Shader Model 6.9 preview driver support. The LibNTC neural texture compression library has also switched the DirectX 12 Cooperative Vector implementation to using the Microsoft Agility SDK Preview rather than NVIDIA custom extensions. This library also has shifted the cooperative vector weight layout conversion work to being done on the GPU(s). There are also LibNTC improvements around channel mappings and improved code quality for inference weight layouts. &lt;br /&gt; &lt;br /&gt;The NVIDIA RTXNTC 0.7 Beta also implements a custom glTF extension "NV_texture_swizzle" for defining NTC storage of materials, improves inference on feedback mode to transcode tiles in batches, improves inference on sample mode, and other improvements. &lt;br /&gt; &lt;br /&gt;Downloads and more details on the NVIDIA RTX Neural Texture Compression 0.7 Beta via &lt;a href="https://github.com/NVIDIA-RTX/RTXNTC/releases/tag/v0.7.0-beta"&gt;GitHub&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/div&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>GNOME Builder &amp; Digital Wellbeing Code Improved This Week</title>
      <author>Michael Larabel</author>
      <link>https://www.phoronix.com/news/GNOME-Builder-Digital-Wellbeing</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.phoronix.com/news/GNOME-Builder-Digital-Wellbeing</guid>
      <pubDate>Sat, 12 Jul 2025 10:43:38 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>&lt;div class="content"&gt; &lt;div style="float: left; padding: 0 10px 10px;"&gt;&lt;img alt="GNOME" src="https://www.phoronix.com/assets/categories/gnome.webp" width="100" height="100" /&gt;&lt;/div&gt; On top of this week's release of the &lt;a href="https://www.phoronix.com/news/GNOME-49-Alpha"&gt;GNOME 49 Alpha&lt;/a&gt;, other application improvements and more came about in the past few days. &lt;br /&gt; &lt;br /&gt;This Week in GNOME is out with their newest issue to outline the notable GNOME desktop changes for the week. Some of the highlights this week included: &lt;br /&gt; &lt;br /&gt;- The GNOME Calendar application now allows exporting events as ICS files for easy event sharing. &lt;br /&gt; &lt;br /&gt;- The GNOME Builder integrated development environment has added built-in inline Git blame support to see who last modified particular lines of code. GNOME Builder also now has enhanced LSP Markdown rendering with syntax highlighting and other enhancements. &lt;br /&gt; &lt;br /&gt;- The third-party Dev Toolbox added a new color converter tool between HEX / RGB / HSL and other color formats. There is also improvements to its JWT and chmod tools as well as enhanced search support and more. &lt;br /&gt; &lt;br /&gt;- The GNOME Foundation continues supporting efforts for advancing the desktop's "Digital Wellbeing" feature as well as working on grant/fellowships and other activities. Part of the Digital Wellbeing sponsorship from the GNOME Foundation is to enhance the Parental Controls support  so it's on-par with other modern GNOME apps. &lt;br /&gt; &lt;br /&gt;More details for those interested via &lt;a href="https://thisweek.gnome.org/posts/2025/07/twig-208/"&gt;This Week in GNOME #208&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/div&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>KDE Preps More Crash KWin Crash Fixes, New Feature Work For Plasma 6.5</title>
      <author>Michael Larabel</author>
      <link>https://www.phoronix.com/news/KDE-Mid-July-2025</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.phoronix.com/news/KDE-Mid-July-2025</guid>
      <pubDate>Sat, 12 Jul 2025 10:13:47 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>&lt;div class="content"&gt; &lt;div style="float: left; padding: 0 10px 10px;"&gt;&lt;img alt="KDE" src="https://www.phoronix.com/assets/categories/kde.webp" width="100" height="100" /&gt;&lt;/div&gt; KDE developer Nate Graham is out with his weekly development recap of all interesting things and fixes merged for the week to Plasma. &lt;br /&gt; &lt;br /&gt;Summer holidays aren't lightening the Plasma 6.5 development activities as it's been another busy week working on new Plasma 6.5 features and further fixes for Plasma 6.4. Some of this week's KDE Plasma highlights include: &lt;br /&gt; &lt;br /&gt;- Plasma 6.5 will now allow configuring rotatable dials on drawing tablets. &lt;br /&gt; &lt;br /&gt;- When sharing the current WiFi network on Plasma 6.5, the WiFi password will be displayed too for easier connection experience. &lt;br /&gt; &lt;br /&gt;- With the recently-introduced ability to change wallpapers between light and dark versions, Plasma 6.5 now is also adding a feature that makes use of the day/night cycle for the wallpaper light/dark switching too. &lt;br /&gt; &lt;br /&gt;- Plasma 6.4.3 has fixed a KWin crash when Alt + Tab out of certain games. There is also another KWin crash while using a drawing tablet pen when an internal window closes. &lt;br /&gt; &lt;br /&gt;- Plasma 6.4.3 also fixes a KWin memory leak. &lt;br /&gt; &lt;br /&gt;More details on this week's KDE fixes and other feature work for Plasma 6.5 via &lt;a href="https://blogs.kde.org/2025/07/12/this-week-in-plasma-tablet-dials-and-day/night-cycles/"&gt;This Week in Plasma&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/div&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Wine 10.12 Released With Experimental EGL Backend For The X11 Driver</title>
      <author>Michael Larabel</author>
      <link>https://www.phoronix.com/news/Wine-10.12-Released</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.phoronix.com/news/Wine-10.12-Released</guid>
      <pubDate>Sat, 12 Jul 2025 00:48:19 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>&lt;div class="content"&gt; &lt;div style="float: left; padding: 0 10px 10px;"&gt;&lt;img alt="WINE" src="https://www.phoronix.com/assets/categories/wine.webp" width="100" height="100" /&gt;&lt;/div&gt; Wine 10.12 has been uncorked as the latest bi-weekly development release of this open-source software running Windows games and applications on Linux and other operating systems. &lt;br /&gt; &lt;br /&gt;While many open-source projects are no longer pursuing enhancements to their X11 code paths, Wine 10.12 does bring some additional work to its X11 driver. Wine 10.12 has gained an optional EGL back-end in the X11 driver for OpenGL contexts as an alternative to the GLX back-end. &lt;br /&gt;&lt;p align="center"&gt;&lt;img src="https://www.phoronix.net/image.php?id=2025&amp;image=wine_egl_x11" alt="Wine EGL X11" /&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;br /&gt;Wine's EGL OpenGL back-end for X11 is currently considered experimental and can be enabled via the "UseEGL" option while in its experimental state. &lt;br /&gt; &lt;br /&gt;Wine 10.12 also adds support for Bluetooth Low Energy (BLE) services, more support for generating Windows Runtime metadata in WIDL, and various bug fixes. &lt;br /&gt; &lt;br /&gt;Wine ARM64 builds are also now enabled in Wine's GitLab continuous integration (CI) for hopefully catching more ARM64-specific issues moving forward. &lt;br /&gt; &lt;br /&gt;There are 17 known bug fixes for the week ranging from Internet Settings issues to older games like Solder of Fortune II crashing. &lt;br /&gt; &lt;br /&gt;Downloads and more details on the Wine 10.12 development release via &lt;a href="https://gitlab.winehq.org/wine/wine/-/releases/wine-10.12"&gt;WineHQ.org&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/div&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Attack Vector Controls Could Be Ready For Linux 6.17 Introduction</title>
      <author>Michael Larabel</author>
      <link>https://www.phoronix.com/news/Attack-Vector-Controls-Coming</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.phoronix.com/news/Attack-Vector-Controls-Coming</guid>
      <pubDate>Fri, 11 Jul 2025 17:02:29 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>&lt;div class="content"&gt; &lt;div style="float: left; padding: 0 10px 10px;"&gt;&lt;img alt="LINUX SECURITY" src="https://www.phoronix.com/assets/categories/linuxsecurity.webp" width="100" height="100" /&gt;&lt;/div&gt; The AMD engineering led work on &lt;a href="https://www.phoronix.com/search/Attack+Vector+Controls"&gt;Attack Vector Controls&lt;/a&gt; for the Linux kernel could be mainlined with the upcoming Linux 6.17 kernel with the remaining patches now being queued within a TIP branch.  &lt;br /&gt;  &lt;br /&gt;Sent out last year were the original patches for Attack Vector Controls as &lt;a href="https://www.phoronix.com/news/Attack-Vector-Controls-RFC"&gt;a way to re-think CPU security mitigation handling&lt;/a&gt;. With Attack Vector Controls it becomes easier for Linux system/server administrators to control which CPU mitigations are applied based upon the intended role of the system, rather than worrying about enabling/disabling individual security mitigations.  &lt;br /&gt;&lt;p align="center"&gt;&lt;img src="https://www.phoronix.net/image.php?id=2025&amp;image=linux_615_amd_intel_med" alt="Intel and AMD processors" /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;br /&gt;Attack Vector Controls &lt;a href="https://www.phoronix.com/news/Linux-CPU-Attack-Vector-Control"&gt;allow much easier mitigation management&lt;/a&gt; by classifying CPU securirty mitigations in areas of user-to-kernel, user-to-user, guest-to-host, guest-to-guest, and cross-thread mitigations. Depending upon whether the server(s) are running any virtual machines, whether the server is running all trusted VMs or a mix of VMs from different untrusted users, and similar scenarios allow for more effective control of these security mitigations across different AMD and Intel processors.  &lt;br /&gt;&lt;p align="center"&gt;&lt;img src="https://www.phoronix.net/image.php?id=2025&amp;image=attack_vectors_table" alt="Attack Vector Controls table" /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;br /&gt;Back in Linux 6.15 &lt;a href="https://www.phoronix.com/news/Linux-6.15-x86-bugs"&gt;some of the preparation patches were merged&lt;/a&gt; while it looks like for Linux 6.17 the actual enablement could be upstreamed.  &lt;br /&gt;&lt;p align="center"&gt;&lt;img src="https://www.phoronix.net/image.php?id=2025&amp;image=attack_vectors_queue" alt="queued patches" /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;br /&gt;Merged today via the &lt;a href="https://git.kernel.org/pub/scm/linux/kernel/git/tip/tip.git/log/?h=x86/bugs"&gt;tip/tip.git's x86/bugs branch&lt;/a&gt; are the Attack Vector Controls patches. Now that the patches are in a TIP branch, they will presumably be submitted for the next kernel cycle: the upcoming Linux 6.17 merge window opening around the end of July / early August.  &lt;br /&gt;  &lt;br /&gt;See &lt;a href="https://git.kernel.org/pub/scm/linux/kernel/git/tip/tip.git/commit/?h=x86/bugs&amp;id=1caa1b0509eaec2ea111b875da4eddb44edc9ea5"&gt;the current Attack Vector Controls documentation&lt;/a&gt; for more information around these upcoming controls for managing CPU security mitigations on Linux systems.&lt;/div&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>AMD Radeon RX 9070 Ray-Tracing Performance Improving With Mesa 25.2</title>
      <author>Michael Larabel</author>
      <link>https://www.phoronix.com/review/mesa-252-radv-rt-rdna4</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.phoronix.com/review/mesa-252-radv-rt-rdna4</guid>
      <pubDate>Fri, 11 Jul 2025 13:48:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>&lt;div class="content"&gt;   &lt;p align="center"&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.phoronix.com/image-viewer.php?id=mesa-252-radv-rt-rdna4&amp;image=amd_rx9070_rt_1_lrg" target="_blank"&gt;&lt;img src="https://www.phoronix.net/image.php?id=mesa-252-radv-rt-rdna4&amp;image=amd_rx9070_rt_1_med" alt="Radeon RX 9070 graphics card" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p&gt;With the feature freeze and code branching for &lt;a href="https://www.phoronix.com/search/Mesa+25.2"&gt;Mesa 25.2&lt;/a&gt; expected to take place next week and kick off the release process for this quarterly Mesa 3D version to debut as stable in August, I've begun running more benchmarks of this latest code on popular GPUs. As it pertains to the newest AMD Radeon RX 9000 series RDNA4 graphics processors, the most exciting area with Mesa 25.2 are the Vulkan ray-tracing improvements. Here is a look at some of what to expect with the upcoming Mesa 25.2 performance for the AMD Radeon RX 9070 graphics card on Linux.&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p align="center"&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.phoronix.com/image-viewer.php?id=mesa-252-radv-rt-rdna4&amp;image=amd_rx9070_rt_2_lrg" target="_blank"&gt;&lt;img src="https://www.phoronix.net/image.php?id=mesa-252-radv-rt-rdna4&amp;image=amd_rx9070_rt_2_med" alt="Radeon RX 9070 graphics on Linux" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p&gt;This is a look at the AMD Radeon RX 9070 performance as found out-of-the-box on Ubuntu 25.04 with its Linux 6.14 + Mesa 25.0 graphics stack compared to upgrading then to the Mesa 25.2-devel state with the "ubuntu/mesaaco" PPA for easy reproducibility. Yes, Mesa 25.1 was out in the interim, but long story short didn't provide any significant differences over 25.0 and the common out-of-the-box experience found on the likes of Ubuntu 25.04. Once the Mesa 25.2 proper release is near, I'll be around with more graphics cards and of doing 25.1 vs. 25.2 specifically. The intent here is just an early preview looking at namely the ray-tracing performance for Ubuntu 25.04 and other non-rolling-release users if upgrading to Mesa 25.2 for helping the performance. The Linux 6.14 kernel was used for both Mesa driver runs.&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;div style="text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;img type="image/svg+xml" width="100%" height="auto" src="https://phoronix.com/benchmark/result/mesa-252-amd-radeon-rdna4-ray-tracing-benchmarks/result.svgz" alt="Mesa 25.2 AMD Radeon RDNA4 Ray-Tracing Benchmarks" /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;  &lt;p&gt;This testing was done on a Gigabyte Radeon RX 9070 16GB graphics card for looking at what's in store with the upcoming Mesa 25.2 release.&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="content"&gt;   &lt;div style="text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;img type="image/svg+xml" width="100%" height="auto" src="//phoronix.com/benchmark/result/mesa-252-amd-radeon-rdna4-ray-tracing-benchmarks/cyberpunk-2077-2560-x-1440-medium.svgz" alt="Cyberpunk 2077 benchmark with settings of Resolution: 2560 x 1440, Graphics Setting: Medium. Mesa 25.2-devel was the fastest." /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;  &lt;div style="text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;img type="image/svg+xml" width="100%" height="auto" src="//phoronix.com/benchmark/result/mesa-252-amd-radeon-rdna4-ray-tracing-benchmarks/cyberpunk-2077-2560-x-1440-high.svgz" alt="Cyberpunk 2077 benchmark with settings of Resolution: 2560 x 1440, Graphics Setting: High. Mesa 25.2-devel was the fastest." /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;  &lt;div style="text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;img type="image/svg+xml" width="100%" height="auto" src="//phoronix.com/benchmark/result/mesa-252-amd-radeon-rdna4-ray-tracing-benchmarks/cyberpunk-2077-2560-x-1440-ultra.svgz" alt="Cyberpunk 2077 benchmark with settings of Resolution: 2560 x 1440, Graphics Setting: Ultra. Mesa 25.2-devel was the fastest." /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;  &lt;div style="text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;img type="image/svg+xml" width="100%" height="auto" src="//phoronix.com/benchmark/result/mesa-252-amd-radeon-rdna4-ray-tracing-benchmarks/cyberpunk-2077-3840-x-2160-high.svgz" alt="Cyberpunk 2077 benchmark with settings of Resolution: 3840 x 2160, Graphics Setting: High. Mesa 25.2-devel was the fastest." /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;  &lt;div style="text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;img type="image/svg+xml" width="100%" height="auto" src="//phoronix.com/benchmark/result/mesa-252-amd-radeon-rdna4-ray-tracing-benchmarks/counter-strike-2-2560-x-1440.svgz" alt="Counter-Strike 2 benchmark with settings of Resolution: 2560 x 1440. Mesa 25.2-devel was the fastest." /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;  &lt;div style="text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;img type="image/svg+xml" width="100%" height="auto" src="//phoronix.com/benchmark/result/mesa-252-amd-radeon-rdna4-ray-tracing-benchmarks/counter-strike-2-3840-x-2160.svgz" alt="Counter-Strike 2 benchmark with settings of Resolution: 3840 x 2160. Mesa 25.2-devel was the fastest." /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;  &lt;p&gt;As noted, Mesa 25.2 is most exciting for AMD Radeon Linux users when it comes to Vulkan ray-tracing specifically while testing for traditional rasterized games the performance was barely changed going back to Mesa 25.0 on Ubuntu 25.04.&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;div style="text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;img type="image/svg+xml" width="100%" height="auto" src="//phoronix.com/benchmark/result/mesa-252-amd-radeon-rdna4-ray-tracing-benchmarks/hitman-3-3840-x-2160-ultra.svgz" alt="HITMAN 3 benchmark with settings of Resolution: 3840 x 2160, Quality Level: Ultra. Ubuntu 25.04 Defaults was the fastest." /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;  &lt;div style="text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;img type="image/svg+xml" width="100%" height="auto" src="//phoronix.com/benchmark/result/mesa-252-amd-radeon-rdna4-ray-tracing-benchmarks/hitman-3-3840-x-2160-ultra-total-frame-time.svgz" alt="HITMAN 3 benchmark with settings of Resolution: 3840 x 2160, Quality Level: Ultra, Total Frame Time. Mesa 25.2-devel was the fastest." /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;  &lt;div style="text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;img type="image/svg+xml" width="100%" height="auto" src="//phoronix.com/benchmark/result/mesa-252-amd-radeon-rdna4-ray-tracing-benchmarks/3dmark-wild-life-extreme-2560-x-1440.svgz" alt="3DMark Wild Life Extreme benchmark with settings of Resolution: 2560 x 1440. Mesa 25.2-devel was the fastest." /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;  &lt;div style="text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;img type="image/svg+xml" width="100%" height="auto" src="//phoronix.com/benchmark/result/mesa-252-amd-radeon-rdna4-ray-tracing-benchmarks/3dmark-wild-life-extreme-3840-x-2160.svgz" alt="3DMark Wild Life Extreme benchmark with settings of Resolution: 3840 x 2160. Mesa 25.2-devel was the fastest." /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;  &lt;p&gt;It is nice though that the Radeon RX 9070 / RDNA4 experience out-of-the-box at launch was in good shape for the likes of Ubuntu 25.04 when it comes to these non-ray-traced games and other graphics benchmarks.&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;div style="text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;img type="image/svg+xml" width="100%" height="auto" src="//phoronix.com/benchmark/result/mesa-252-amd-radeon-rdna4-ray-tracing-benchmarks/unigine-superposition-3840-x-2160-fullscreen-low-opengl.svgz" alt="Unigine Superposition benchmark with settings of Resolution: 3840 x 2160, Mode: Fullscreen, Quality: Low, Renderer: OpenGL. Ubuntu 25.04 Defaults was the fastest." /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;  &lt;div style="text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;img type="image/svg+xml" width="100%" height="auto" src="//phoronix.com/benchmark/result/mesa-252-amd-radeon-rdna4-ray-tracing-benchmarks/unigine-superposition-3840-x-2160-fullscreen-medium-opengl.svgz" alt="Unigine Superposition benchmark with settings of Resolution: 3840 x 2160, Mode: Fullscreen, Quality: Medium, Renderer: OpenGL. Ubuntu 25.04 Defaults was the fastest." /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;  &lt;div style="text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;img type="image/svg+xml" width="100%" height="auto" src="//phoronix.com/benchmark/result/mesa-252-amd-radeon-rdna4-ray-tracing-benchmarks/unigine-superposition-3840-x-2160-fullscreen-high-opengl.svgz" alt="Unigine Superposition benchmark with settings of Resolution: 3840 x 2160, Mode: Fullscreen, Quality: High, Renderer: OpenGL. Ubuntu 25.04 Defaults was the fastest." /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;  &lt;div style="text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;img type="image/svg+xml" width="100%" height="auto" src="//phoronix.com/benchmark/result/mesa-252-amd-radeon-rdna4-ray-tracing-benchmarks/gravitymark-2560-x-1440-opengl.svgz" alt="GravityMark benchmark with settings of Resolution: 2560 x 1440, Renderer: OpenGL. Ubuntu 25.04 Defaults was the fastest." /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;  &lt;p&gt;For OpenGL workloads with the RadeonSI Gallium3D driver, Mesa 25.2 also didn't offer any performance enhancements there with this Radeon RX 9070 testing paired with Linux 6.14.&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;div style="text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;img type="image/svg+xml" width="100%" height="auto" src="//phoronix.com/benchmark/result/mesa-252-amd-radeon-rdna4-ray-tracing-benchmarks/gpuscore-breaking-limit-2560-x-1440-off.svgz" alt="GPUScore: Breaking Limit benchmark with settings of Resolution: 2560 x 1440, Ray-Tracing: Off. Ubuntu 25.04 Defaults was the fastest." /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;  &lt;div style="text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;img type="image/svg+xml" width="100%" height="auto" src="//phoronix.com/benchmark/result/mesa-252-amd-radeon-rdna4-ray-tracing-benchmarks/gpuscore-breaking-limit-2560-x-1440-on.svgz" alt="GPUScore: Breaking Limit benchmark with settings of Resolution: 2560 x 1440, Ray-Tracing: On. Mesa 25.2-devel was the fastest." /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;  &lt;div style="text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;img type="image/svg+xml" width="100%" height="auto" src="//phoronix.com/benchmark/result/mesa-252-amd-radeon-rdna4-ray-tracing-benchmarks/gpuscore-breaking-limit-3840-x-2160-off.svgz" alt="GPUScore: Breaking Limit benchmark with settings of Resolution: 3840 x 2160, Ray-Tracing: Off. Ubuntu 25.04 Defaults was the fastest." /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;  &lt;div style="text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;img type="image/svg+xml" width="100%" height="auto" src="//phoronix.com/benchmark/result/mesa-252-amd-radeon-rdna4-ray-tracing-benchmarks/gpuscore-breaking-limit-3840-x-2160-on.svgz" alt="GPUScore: Breaking Limit benchmark with settings of Resolution: 3840 x 2160, Ray-Tracing: On. Mesa 25.2-devel was the fastest." /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;  &lt;p&gt;But when hitting the Vulkan ray-tracing tests is where Mesa 25.2 began providing some measurable improvements over prior Mesa releases for the RADV driver.&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="content"&gt;   &lt;div style="text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;img type="image/svg+xml" width="100%" height="auto" src="//phoronix.com/benchmark/result/mesa-252-amd-radeon-rdna4-ray-tracing-benchmarks/gravitymark-2560-x-1440-vulkan.svgz" alt="GravityMark benchmark with settings of Resolution: 2560 x 1440, Renderer: Vulkan. Mesa 25.2-devel was the fastest." /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;  &lt;div style="text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;img type="image/svg+xml" width="100%" height="auto" src="//phoronix.com/benchmark/result/mesa-252-amd-radeon-rdna4-ray-tracing-benchmarks/gravitymark-2560-x-1440-vulkan-ray-tracing.svgz" alt="GravityMark benchmark with settings of Resolution: 2560 x 1440, Renderer: Vulkan Ray-Tracing. Mesa 25.2-devel was the fastest." /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;  &lt;div style="text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;img type="image/svg+xml" width="100%" height="auto" src="//phoronix.com/benchmark/result/mesa-252-amd-radeon-rdna4-ray-tracing-benchmarks/gravitymark-3840-x-2160-vulkan.svgz" alt="GravityMark benchmark with settings of Resolution: 3840 x 2160, Renderer: Vulkan. Mesa 25.2-devel was the fastest." /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;  &lt;div style="text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;img type="image/svg+xml" width="100%" height="auto" src="//phoronix.com/benchmark/result/mesa-252-amd-radeon-rdna4-ray-tracing-benchmarks/gravitymark-3840-x-2160-vulkan-ray-tracing.svgz" alt="GravityMark benchmark with settings of Resolution: 3840 x 2160, Renderer: Vulkan Ray-Tracing. Mesa 25.2-devel was the fastest." /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;  &lt;p&gt;With the demanding GravityMark Vulkan benchmark, the ray-traced scenes enjoyed significant gains on the AMD Radeon RX 9070 under Linux. The Vulkan ray-tracing performance for GravityMark was around 16% faster with Mesa 25.2-devel compared to the Ubuntu 25.04 out-of-the-box performance on this RDNA4 graphics card.&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;div style="text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;img type="image/svg+xml" width="100%" height="auto" src="//phoronix.com/benchmark/result/mesa-252-amd-radeon-rdna4-ray-tracing-benchmarks/gravitymark-3840-x-2160-vulkan-ray-tracing-1.svgz" alt="GravityMark benchmark with settings of Resolution: 3840 x 2160, Renderer: Vulkan Ray-Tracing. Mesa 25.2-devel was the fastest." /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;  &lt;p&gt;Also worth noting is that there wasn't any significant power difference for the Radeon RX 9070 with this faster ray-tracing performance.&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;div style="text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;img type="image/svg+xml" width="100%" height="auto" src="//phoronix.com/benchmark/result/mesa-252-amd-radeon-rdna4-ray-tracing-benchmarks/ray-tracing-in-vulkan-3840-x-2160-rtiow.svgz" alt="Ray Tracing In Vulkan benchmark with settings of Resolution: 3840 x 2160, Scene: Ray Tracing In One Weekend. Mesa 25.2-devel was the fastest." /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;  &lt;div style="text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;img type="image/svg+xml" width="100%" height="auto" src="//phoronix.com/benchmark/result/mesa-252-amd-radeon-rdna4-ray-tracing-benchmarks/ray-tracing-in-vulkan-3840-x-2160-piow.svgz" alt="Ray Tracing In Vulkan benchmark with settings of Resolution: 3840 x 2160, Scene: Planets In One Weekend. Mesa 25.2-devel was the fastest." /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;  &lt;div style="text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;img type="image/svg+xml" width="100%" height="auto" src="//phoronix.com/benchmark/result/mesa-252-amd-radeon-rdna4-ray-tracing-benchmarks/ray-tracing-in-vulkan-3840-x-2160-liow.svgz" alt="Ray Tracing In Vulkan benchmark with settings of Resolution: 3840 x 2160, Scene: Lucy In One Weekend. Mesa 25.2-devel was the fastest." /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;  &lt;p&gt;Long story short, the Radeon ray-tracing performance with the RADV Vulkan driver is the exciting aspect to look at for Mesa 25.2 and the main area improvement for RDNA4 compared to the out-of-the-box performance on the likes of Ubuntu 25.04. More Mesa 25.2 benchmarks on other Radeon GPUs as well as Intel and NVIDIA/NVK hardware coming soon ahead of the Mesa 25.2 stable release in August.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description>
    </item>
